# Accessibility (A11y)

> **Reference**: This guide extends the [UX/UI Design Principles](../ux-ui.mdc). Make sure you're familiar with core UX/UI principles before diving into accessibility specifics.

## üìã Overview

Accessibility ensures that websites and applications are usable by everyone, including people with disabilities. This includes visual, auditory, motor, and cognitive impairments. Accessible design benefits all users, not just those with disabilities.

**Why it matters:**
- A significant share of users has permanent or temporary impairments (vision, hearing, motor, cognitive).
- Accessibility is often a **legal requirement** (e.g., ADA, Section 508, European Accessibility Act).
- Accessible design improves usability for everyone (keyboard power-users, mobile users, users in bright environments, aging users).
- **WCAG 3.0 (2026)**: The upcoming WCAG 3.0 standard introduces more flexible, outcome-oriented accessibility guidelines that focus on user outcomes rather than rigid technical requirements. Design with outcomes in mind‚Äîcan users accomplish their goals?‚Äînot just checkbox compliance.

## üéØ Core Accessibility Principles (POUR)

### 1. Perceivable
Information must be presentable to users in ways they can perceive:
- Text alternatives for images
- Captions for audio/video
- Sufficient color contrast
- Resizable text

### 2. Operable
Interface must be operable by all users:
- Keyboard accessible
- Sufficient time to read/use
- No seizure-inducing content
- Clear navigation

### 3. Understandable
Information and interface must be understandable:
- Readable text
- Predictable functionality
- Input assistance (error messages)
- Consistent navigation

### 4. Robust
Content must work with assistive technologies:
- Valid HTML
- Compatible with screen readers
- Future-proof markup
- Progressive enhancement

## ‚úÖ DO (Recommended Practices)

### Semantic HTML

#### Use Appropriate Elements
- ‚úÖ **Use native HTML elements**: Better accessibility built-in
- ‚úÖ **Proper heading hierarchy**: h1 ‚Üí h2 ‚Üí h3 (don't skip)
- ‚úÖ **Semantic landmarks**: `<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<footer>`
- ‚úÖ **Lists for list content**: `<ul>`, `<ol>`, `<dl>`

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Semantic HTML structure -->
<a href="#main-content">Skip to main content</a>

<header>
  <nav aria-label="Main navigation">
    <ul>
      <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
      <li><a href="/about">About</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
</header>

<main id="main-content">
  <article>
    <h1>Article Title</h1>
    <section>
      <h2>First Section</h2>
      <h3>Subsection</h3>
    </section>
  </article>
</main>
```

> **Reference**: See [HTML Best Practices](../../html/html.mdc) for detailed semantic HTML structure and accessibility guidelines.

#### Buttons vs Links
- ‚úÖ **`<button>` for actions**: Submit, open, toggle
- ‚úÖ **`<a>` for navigation**: Going to another page
- ‚úÖ **Never use `<div>` or `<span>` for clickable elements**

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Proper elements -->
<button type="button">Open Modal</button>
<button type="submit">Submit</button>
<a href="/about">About</a>

<!-- ‚ùå Bad: Div/span as button -->
<div onclick="openModal()">Open Modal</div>
```

> **Reference**: See [HTML Best Practices](../../html/html.mdc) for semantic HTML and proper element usage.

### ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications)

#### ARIA Roles
- ‚úÖ **Use native HTML first**: ARIA should supplement, not replace
- ‚úÖ **Role when needed**: `role="button"`, `role="dialog"`, etc.
- ‚úÖ **Landmark roles**: For better navigation
- ‚úÖ **Don't override native semantics**

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: ARIA for custom components -->
<div role="dialog" aria-labelledby="modal-title" aria-modal="true">
  <h2 id="modal-title">Confirm Action</h2>
  <button>Cancel</button>
  <button>Delete</button>
</div>
```

#### ARIA Labels and Descriptions
- ‚úÖ **`aria-label`**: Provides label when none visible
- ‚úÖ **`aria-labelledby`**: References visible label
- ‚úÖ **`aria-describedby`**: Additional description
- ‚úÖ **`aria-hidden`**: Hides decorative elements from screen readers

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: ARIA labels -->
<button aria-label="Close dialog">
  <svg aria-hidden="true"><use href="#icon-close"></use></svg>
</button>

<!-- ‚úÖ Good: aria-describedby -->
<label for="password">Password</label>
<input type="password" id="password" aria-describedby="password-hint">
<span id="password-hint">Must be at least 8 characters</span>
```

#### ARIA States and Properties
- ‚úÖ **`aria-expanded`**: For collapsible content
- ‚úÖ **`aria-checked`**: For custom checkboxes
- ‚úÖ **`aria-disabled`**: For disabled elements
- ‚úÖ **`aria-invalid`**: For form validation
- ‚úÖ **`aria-live`**: For dynamic content updates

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Accordion with ARIA -->
<button aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="section-1">
  Section 1
</button>
<div id="section-1" hidden>Content</div>

<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Form validation -->
<label for="email">Email</label>
<input type="email" id="email" aria-invalid="true" aria-describedby="email-error">
<span id="email-error" role="alert">Please enter a valid email</span>

<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Live region -->
<div role="status" aria-live="polite">Notification message</div>
```

### Keyboard Navigation

#### Focus Management
- ‚úÖ **All interactive elements focusable**: Tab index 0 or native
- ‚úÖ **Visible focus indicators**: Clear outline or ring
- ‚úÖ **Logical tab order**: Follows visual layout
- ‚úÖ **Skip links**: Jump to main content

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Keyboard accessible -->
<div role="button" tabindex="0">Custom Button</div>
```

```css
/* ‚úÖ Good: Clear focus indicator */
button:focus,
a:focus {
  outline: 3px solid #0066cc;
  outline-offset: 2px;
}
```

#### Keyboard Shortcuts
- ‚úÖ **Standard shortcuts**: Tab, Shift+Tab, Enter, Space, Escape
- ‚úÖ **Arrow keys**: For lists, menus, sliders
- ‚úÖ **Home/End**: Jump to start/end
- ‚úÖ **Document shortcuts**: Avoid conflicting with browser

```javascript
// ‚úÖ Good: Keyboard navigation
dropdown.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
  if (e.key === 'ArrowDown') {
    // Move to next option
  } else if (e.key === 'Enter' || e.key === ' ') {
    // Select option
  } else if (e.key === 'Escape') {
    // Close dropdown
  }
});
```

### Images and Media

#### Alternative Text
- ‚úÖ **Descriptive alt text**: Describe image purpose/content
- ‚úÖ **Empty alt for decorative**: `alt=""`
- ‚úÖ **Don't use "image of"**: Screen readers announce it's an image
- ‚úÖ **Keep concise**: 125 characters or less

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Descriptive alt text -->
<img src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing sales increased 50% in Q4">

<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Empty alt for decorative -->
<img src="decorative.png" alt="">

<!-- ‚ùå Bad: Missing or generic alt -->
<img src="photo.jpg" alt="image">
<img src="logo.png">
```

> **Reference**: See [HTML Best Practices](../../html/html.mdc) for detailed image accessibility guidelines.

#### Video and Audio
- ‚úÖ **Captions for videos**: For deaf/hard of hearing
- ‚úÖ **Transcripts for audio**: Full text alternative
- ‚úÖ **Audio descriptions**: Narrate visual content
- ‚úÖ **Controls accessible**: Keyboard operable

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Video with captions -->
<video controls>
  <source src="video.mp4" type="video/mp4">
  <track kind="captions" src="captions.vtt" srclang="en" default>
</video>

<details>
  <summary>Video Transcript</summary>
  <p>Full text transcript...</p>
</details>
```

### Forms Accessibility

#### Labels and Instructions
- ‚úÖ **Explicit labels**: Always use `<label>` element
- ‚úÖ **Required fields marked**: Visual and programmatic
- ‚úÖ **Clear instructions**: Before form, not just in errors
- ‚úÖ **Error identification**: Specific and helpful

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Accessible form -->
<form>
  <label for="name">Full Name *</label>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required aria-required="true">
  
  <label for="email">Email Address *</label>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required aria-required="true">
  
  <fieldset>
    <legend>Contact Preference</legend>
    <input type="radio" id="contact-email" name="contact" value="email">
    <label for="contact-email">Email</label>
  </fieldset>
  
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>
```

> **Reference**: See [Forms and Validation](forms-validation.mdc) for detailed form accessibility patterns. See [HTML Best Practices](../../html/html.mdc) for semantic HTML form structure.

### Color Contrast

#### WCAG Requirements
- ‚úÖ **Normal text**: 4.5:1 minimum (AA), 7:1 (AAA)
- ‚úÖ **Large text**: 3:1 minimum (AA), 4.5:1 (AAA)
- ‚úÖ **UI components**: 3:1 minimum
- ‚úÖ **Test all combinations**: Use contrast checkers

```css
/* ‚úÖ Good: Sufficient contrast */
:root {
  --text-primary: #111827;
  --text-secondary: #6b7280;
  --link-color: #0066cc;
}

/* ‚ùå Bad: Insufficient contrast */
.low-contrast {
  color: #cccccc;
  background: #ffffff;
}
```

> **Reference**: See [Colors and Contrast](../visual/colors-contrast.mdc) for detailed contrast requirements and testing.

### Screen Reader Support

#### Screen Reader Only Text
- ‚úÖ **Visually hidden, screen reader visible**
- ‚úÖ **Additional context for SR users**
- ‚úÖ **Don't use `display: none` or `visibility: hidden`**

```html
<!-- ‚úÖ Good: Screen reader only text -->
<a href="/article">
  Read more
  <span class="sr-only">about our new product launch</span>
</a>
```

```css
/* ‚úÖ Good: Screen reader only */
.sr-only {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
}
```

## ‚ùå DON'T (Anti-patterns)

### Semantic HTML Mistakes
- ‚ùå **Div/span for buttons/links**: Not accessible
- ‚ùå **Skipping heading levels**: h1 ‚Üí h3 (skip h2)
- ‚ùå **Multiple h1 per page**: Confuses hierarchy
- ‚ùå **Tables for layout**: Use CSS Grid/Flexbox

### ARIA Mistakes
- ‚ùå **Overusing ARIA**: Use native HTML first
- ‚ùå **Conflicting roles**: Don't override native semantics
- ‚ùå **Incorrect relationships**: aria-labelledby pointing to non-existent ID
- ‚ùå **Missing required attributes**: role="button" without tabindex

### Keyboard Mistakes
- ‚ùå **Removing focus indicators**: Never `outline: none` without alternative
- ‚ùå **Non-focusable interactives**: Div buttons without tabindex
- ‚ùå **Focus traps**: Can't escape modal/dropdown
- ‚ùå **Illogical tab order**: Using tabindex > 0

### Content Mistakes
- ‚ùå **Missing alt text**: Empty or missing alt attributes
- ‚ùå **Color-only information**: "Click the red button"
- ‚ùå **Auto-playing media**: Without controls or way to stop
- ‚ùå **Time limits**: Without way to extend or disable

## üìù Accessibility Checklist

Before launching, verify:
- [ ] All images have appropriate alt text
- [ ] Color contrast meets WCAG AA (4.5:1 for text)
- [ ] All functionality available via keyboard
- [ ] Focus indicators are clearly visible
- [ ] Proper heading hierarchy (h1 ‚Üí h2 ‚Üí h3)
- [ ] Form inputs have explicit labels
- [ ] Error messages are clear and associated with fields
- [ ] ARIA labels where needed (icons, custom controls)
- [ ] Videos have captions/transcripts
- [ ] Page has descriptive `<title>`
- [ ] Language is declared (`<html lang="en">`)
- [ ] Skip links for keyboard users
- [ ] Responsive text (zoom to 200%)
- [ ] Tested with screen reader (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)
- [ ] No keyboard traps

## üìä WCAG Compliance Levels

| Level | Description | Requirements |
|-------|-------------|--------------|
| **A** | Minimum | Essential accessibility features |
| **AA** | Recommended | Standard for most sites (legal requirement) |
| **AAA** | Optimal | Enhanced accessibility (not always possible) |

**Target**: WCAG **2.2** Level **AA** compliance minimum (2.1 AA as baseline where needed). Note: WCAG 3.0 introduces more flexible, outcome-oriented standards. When WCAG 3.0 becomes official, prioritize outcome-based accessibility over rigid point-based compliance.

## üìù Key Points

### Must Have
- Semantic HTML elements
- Keyboard accessibility for all interactions
- Sufficient color contrast (4.5:1 minimum)
- Alt text for all meaningful images
- Explicit form labels
- Visible focus indicators
- ARIA where native HTML insufficient

### Do
- Use native HTML elements first
- Test with keyboard only
- Test with screen readers
- Provide multiple ways to access content
- Use clear, plain language
- Provide text alternatives for media
- Maintain logical heading hierarchy
- Include skip links

### Don't
- Don't use div/span for buttons/links
- Don't remove focus indicators without replacement
- Don't rely on color alone
- Don't auto-play videos/audio
- Don't use ARIA when native HTML works
- Don't skip heading levels
- Don't forget alt text
- Don't create keyboard traps

